  "prompt": "How did Gods of Egypt get greenlit? What's the backstory of how the movie got made?",
  "response": "\"Gods of Egypt\" is a 2016 fantasy action film directed by Alex Proyas, known for his work on \"The Crow\" and \"Dark City.\" The movie was produced by Summit Entertainment and distributed by Lionsgate. The backstory of how \"Gods of Egypt\" got greenlit is an interesting tale of a Hollywood gamble that didn't quite pay off as hoped. Here\u2019s a detailed look at the journey of the film from concept to completion:\n\n### Concept and Development\nThe idea for \"Gods of Egypt\" originated from a script by Matt Sazama and Burk Sharpless. The duo had previously worked on \"Dracula Untold,\" another attempt at a mythological epic. Their script for \"Gods of Egypt\" was inspired by ancient Egyptian mythology, reimagined with a modern, action-packed twist.\n\n### Pitch and Greenlighting\nThe script was pitched to Summit Entertainment, which saw potential in the blend of mythological storytelling and big-budget action sequences. The studio likely hoped to replicate the success of films like \"Clash of the Titans\" and \"Immortals,\" which had managed to turn ancient myths into lucrative blockbusters.\n\nAlex Proyas, with his experience in visually striking and genre-bending films, was an appealing choice for director. His involvement likely played a significant role in getting the project greenlit, as he had a track record of delivering visually ambitious projects.\n\n### Casting and Controversy\nOne of the most controversial aspects of \"Gods of Egypt\" was its casting. The film faced significant criticism for \"whitewashing,\" as many of the leading roles, which were supposed to represent ancient Egyptian gods and characters, were played by white actors. This included Gerard Butler as Set, Nikolaj Coster-Waldau as Horus, and Brenton Thwaites as Bek.\n\nThe casting decisions were widely criticized, and the film's producers issued an apology, stating that they had aimed to create a fantastical world and did not intend to offend. Despite this, the controversy contributed to the film's poor reception.\n\n### Production and Budget\n\"Gods of Egypt\" was made with a hefty budget of around $140 million. The film utilized extensive special effects, including CGI and practical effects, to bring the mythological world to life. The production was primarily shot in Australia, taking advantage of local tax incentives and state-of-the-art facilities.\n\n### Marketing and Release\nThe marketing campaign for \"Gods of Egypt\" emphasized its grand scale and action-packed sequences. Trailers and promotional materials promised epic battles and a visually stunning depiction of ancient Egypt. However, the film's negative buzz, particularly around the casting controversy, overshadowed these efforts.\n\nUpon its release in February 2016, \"Gods of Egypt\" received overwhelmingly negative reviews from critics. It holds a low 15% rating on Rotten Tomatoes, with many reviewers criticizing its lack of originality, poor storytelling, and the aforementioned casting issues.\n\n### Box Office Performance\nDespite its ambitious budget and marketing, \"Gods of Egypt\" underperformed at the box office. It grossed around $150 million worldwide, failing to recoup its production and marketing costs. The film's financial failure led to it being considered a significant box office bomb.\n\n### Aftermath and Legacy\nThe failure of \"Gods of Egypt\" serves as a cautionary tale in Hollywood about the risks of high-budget projects with controversial elements. It sparked discussions about diversity and representation in film, contributing to broader conversations about inclusivity in the industry.\n\nIn summary, \"Gods of Egypt\" was greenlit based on the potential for a visually spectacular and action-driven mythological epic. However, it was ultimately undone by a combination of poor critical reception, casting controversies, and financial underperformance.",
